"Piontkovski S.A., Castellani C.","Long-term declining trend of zooplankton biomass in the Tropical Atlantic",2009,"Hydrobiologia","632","1",,"365","370",,,10.1007/s10750-009-9854-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70349997062&partnerID=40&md5=11457e38d586b4d2468f7b77af01ba28","Sultan Qaboos University, P.O. Box 34, Al-Khod 123, Muscat, Oman; Sir Alistair Hardy Foundation for Ocean Science (SAHFOS), The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth, Devon PL1 2PB, United Kingdom","Piontkovski, S.A., Sultan Qaboos University, P.O. Box 34, Al-Khod 123, Muscat, Oman; Castellani, C., Sir Alistair Hardy Foundation for Ocean Science (SAHFOS), The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth, Devon PL1 2PB, United Kingdom","We report evidences that the zooplankton biomass in the tropical Atlantic has declined with an almost 10-fold drop from the 1950s to 2000. The results of the multiple regression analysis showed that the decline in zooplankton biomass was positively related to the NAO-index and to phosphate concentration. We also found that the depth of the thermocline has decreased over the period of our investigation. Thus, the decline we report in zooplankton biomass may be related to the combined effect of two phenomena driven by global temperature increase: (1) the widening of the distributional range of tropical species due to the expansion of the 'tropical belt' and (2) a decrease in primary production resulting from the thinning of the thermocline. The decline of zooplankton biomass we report suggests that global warming of the ocean may be altering tropical food webs, and through them, it may also indirectly impact tropical oceans biogeochemical cycles. © Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2009.","Atlantic Ocean; NAO; Time series; Zooplankton","Atlantic Ocean; Biogeochemical cycle; Combined effect; Food webs; Global temperatures; Multiple regression analysis; NAO; Phosphate concentration; Primary production; Tropical atlantic; Tropical belt; Tropical ocean; Tropical species; Zooplankton; Analytical geochemistry; Arctic engineering; Biogeochemistry; Biomass; Global warming; Oceanography; Regression analysis; Stream flow; Time series; Tropics; biogeochemical cycle; biomass; food web; global warming; multiple regression; North Atlantic Oscillation; phosphate; primary production; temperature effect; thermocline; time series; zooplankton; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (Tropical)",,,,,,"Barry, J.P., Baxter, C.H., Sagarin, R.D., Gilman, S.E., Climate-related, long-term faunal changes in a California rocky intertidal community (1995) Science, 267, pp. 672-675; Bates, N.R., Pequignet, A.C., Johnson, R., Gruber, N., A short term sink for atmospheric CO2 in subtropical mode water of the North Atlantic Ocean (2002) Nature, 420, pp. 489-493; Beaugrand, G., The North Sea regime shift: Evidence, causes, mechanisms and consequences (2004) Progress in Oceanography, 60, pp. 245-262; Beaugrand, G., Reid, P.C., Ibañez, F., Lindley, J.A., Edwards, M., Reorganization of North Atlantic marine copepod biodiversity and climate (2002) Science, 296, pp. 1692-1694; Behrenfeld, M.J., Falkowski, P.G., Photosynthetic rates derived from satellite-based chlorophyll concentration (1997) Limnology and Oceanography, 42, pp. 1-20; Behrenfeld, M.J., O'Malley, R.T., Siegel, D.A., McClain, C.R., Sarmiento, J.L., Feldman, G.C., Milligan, A.J., Boss, E.S., Climate-driven trends in contemporary ocean productivity (2006) Nature, 44, pp. 752-755; http://www.decvar.org/newsletter/vol1.1/wainer.html, Campos, C. N., M. Goes, A. S. Taschetto & I. Wainer, 2001. Subtle Signals Newsletter 1Christian, J.R., Murtugudde, R., Tropical Atlantic variability in a coupled physical-biogeochemical ocean model (2003) Deep-Sea Research II, 50, pp. 2947-2969; Cushing, D. H., 1975. Marine ecology and fisheries. Cambridge University Press, London: 278ppDoney, S.C., Oceanography: Plankton in a warmer world (2006) Nature, 444, pp. 695-696; Finenko, Z.Z., Piontkovski, S.A., Williams, R., Mi